<Layout title="Few-Shot Prompting">
    <div class="container">
        <h1>üìé Few-Shot Prompting</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">
            Teach the AI with examples instead of just instructions ‚Äî and unlock
            tasks zero-shot can't handle
        </p>
        <div class="doc-link">
            <a
                href="https://www.promptingguide.ai/techniques/fewshot"
                target="_blank">üìÑ View Original Docs ‚Äî promptingguide.ai</a
            >
        </div>

        <!-- Core concept -->
        <div class="section-title">üí° What Is Few-Shot Prompting?</div>
        <div class="card purple">
            <h3>Show. Don't just tell.</h3>
            <p>
                Few-shot prompting means giving the AI <strong
                    style="color:#e2e8f0;"
                    >a few examples (demonstrations)</strong
                > of the task before asking it to do the real thing. Instead of just
                writing an instruction, you show input‚Üíoutput pairs so the AI learns
                the pattern, format, and logic in context ‚Äî on the fly, without any
                retraining.
            </p>
            <div class="analogy">
                üß† <strong>Analogy:</strong> Imagine you're teaching an intern a new
                task. You could write a manual (zero-shot), or you could sit next
                to them and say "look ‚Äî here's input, here's what the output should
                look like. Now you try." That's few-shot. The intern learns from your
                live examples much faster than from the manual.
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- The core example: inventing a word -->
        <div class="section-title">
            üìã The Key Example ‚Äî Teaching an Invented Word
        </div>
        <p
            style="font-size:0.84rem;color:#94a3b8;line-height:1.65;margin-bottom:0.8rem;"
        >
            The page uses a brilliant example: a made-up word (<em>whatpu</em>)
            that the AI has never seen. One example is enough for it to
            understand and use a second made-up word (<em>farduddle</em>)
            correctly ‚Äî that's <strong style="color:#e2e8f0;"
                >in-context learning</strong
            > in action.
        </p>
        <div class="prompt-wrap">
            <div class="lbl">
                1-SHOT PROMPT ‚Äî one example, then the real task
            </div>
            <pre><span class="hl-ex">A "whatpu" is a small, furry animal native to Tanzania. An example of a sentence that uses the word whatpu is:
We were traveling in Africa and we saw these very cute whatpus.</span>

<span class="hl-task">To do a "farduddle" means to jump up and down really fast. An example of a sentence that uses the word farduddle is:</span></pre>
        </div>
        <div class="output-wrap">
            <div class="lbl">OUTPUT</div>
            <pre>When we won the game, we all started to farduddle in celebration.</pre>
        </div>

        <div class="two-col">
            <div class="card purple">
                <h3>üîÆ What did the example teach the AI?</h3>
                <p>
                    The first example (whatpu) showed the AI the <em
                        >template</em
                    >: definition ‚Üí sentence using the word naturally. The AI
                    learned the pattern and applied it to farduddle ‚Äî a word it
                    has never seen in its training data. This is pure in-context
                    learning.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card green">
                <h3>‚ö° What would happen without it?</h3>
                <p>
                    Without the whatpu example, the AI would be confused ‚Äî
                    "farduddle" doesn't exist in its knowledge. It might make up
                    a definition, refuse to answer, or produce a grammatically
                    correct but semantically random sentence. The example is the
                    anchor.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- How many shots? Interactive -->
        <div class="section-title">
            üéØ How Many Examples Should You Give? ‚Äî Interactive
        </div>
        <p
            style="font-size:0.84rem;color:#94a3b8;margin-bottom:0.8rem;line-height:1.65;"
        >
            The number of examples ("shots") directly affects quality. Click
            each to understand the tradeoff:
        </p>
        <div class="shot-counter">
            <div class="shot-pill s0 active" onclick="showShot('0', this)">
                0-shot
            </div>
            <div class="shot-pill s1" onclick="showShot('1', this)">1-shot</div>
            <div class="shot-pill s3" onclick="showShot('3', this)">3-shot</div>
            <div class="shot-pill s5" onclick="showShot('5', this)">5-shot</div>
            <div class="shot-pill s10" onclick="showShot('10', this)">
                10-shot
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="shot-content active" id="shot-0">
            <div class="card purple">
                <h3>‚ö° 0-Shot ‚Äî No examples</h3><p>
                    Just an instruction. Works for common, well-known tasks.
                    Format and style are unpredictable ‚Äî the AI decides how to
                    present the output based on its defaults. <strong
                        style="color:#e2e8f0;">Start here always.</strong
                    > If output is good, stop.
                </p><div class="analogy">
                    Like asking a skilled professional to do something they've
                    done many times. No guidance needed.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="shot-content" id="shot-1">
            <div class="card" style="border-left:4px solid #6366f1">
                <h3>üìé 1-Shot ‚Äî One example</h3><p>
                    One input‚Üíoutput pair. Enough to teach format, tone, and
                    basic pattern. <strong style="color:#e2e8f0;"
                        >Covers 80% of use cases</strong
                    > where you need a specific output style. Best starting point
                    after zero-shot fails.
                </p><div
                    class="analogy"
                    style="background:#12151f;border-radius:8px;padding:0.65rem 0.9rem;margin-top:0.7rem;font-size:0.82rem;color:#a78bfa;font-style:italic;"
                >
                    Like showing a cook "this is how the dish should look on the
                    plate" ‚Äî one photo is usually enough.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="shot-content" id="shot-3">
            <div class="card green">
                <h3>üìéüìéüìé 3-Shot ‚Äî Three examples</h3><p>
                    Covers edge cases and nuance. <strong style="color:#e2e8f0;"
                        >Research sweet spot</strong
                    > ‚Äî 3 examples typically gives the AI enough variety to handle
                    diverse inputs confidently. Use when 1-shot still produces inconsistent
                    results. Include a tricky/borderline case.
                </p><div
                    class="analogy"
                    style="background:#12151f;border-radius:8px;padding:0.65rem 0.9rem;margin-top:0.7rem;font-size:0.82rem;color:#4ade80;font-style:italic;"
                >
                    Like showing 3 different version of a dish ‚Äî now the cook
                    understands the range of what's acceptable.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="shot-content" id="shot-5">
            <div class="card orange">
                <h3>üìé√ó5 5-Shot ‚Äî Five examples</h3><p>
                    For complex or unusual tasks where the AI keeps getting it
                    wrong. Adds more diversity to the pattern space. <strong
                        style="color:#e2e8f0;">Watch your token limit</strong
                    > ‚Äî each example eats into the context window. Start seeing diminishing
                    returns here.
                </p><div
                    class="analogy"
                    style="background:#12151f;border-radius:8px;padding:0.65rem 0.9rem;margin-top:0.7rem;font-size:0.82rem;color:#fbbf24;font-style:italic;"
                >
                    Good for tasks with a wide range of valid inputs ‚Äî the more
                    variety in your examples, the more robust the AI becomes.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="shot-content" id="shot-10">
            <div class="card red">
                <h3>üìé√ó10 10-Shot ‚Äî Ten examples</h3><p>
                    Reserved for very complex, domain-specific tasks.
                    Significant token cost. <strong style="color:#e2e8f0;"
                        >If 10-shot still fails</strong
                    > on reasoning or logic tasks, the technique itself has hit its
                    ceiling ‚Äî move to Chain-of-Thought or fine-tuning.
                </p><div
                    class="analogy"
                    style="background:#12151f;border-radius:8px;padding:0.65rem 0.9rem;margin-top:0.7rem;font-size:0.82rem;color:#fb7185;font-style:italic;"
                >
                    Like giving a whole portfolio of examples. Powerful, but
                    expensive. Know when to stop ‚Äî more examples ‚â† always
                    better.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Research findings -->
        <div class="section-title">
            üî¨ Surprising Research Findings ‚Äî What Actually Matters in Examples
        </div>
        <p
            style="font-size:0.84rem;color:#94a3b8;margin-bottom:1rem;line-height:1.65;"
        >
            The page cites research (Min et al. 2022) that revealed some
            counterintuitive truths about what makes few-shot examples work.
            These are genuinely surprising:
        </p>

        <div class="finding">
            <div class="f-icon">üè∑Ô∏è</div>
            <div class="f-body">
                <h4>
                    Finding 1: The labels don't need to be correct ‚Äî the format
                    matters more
                </h4>
                <p>
                    Research showed that even with <strong style="color:#fff;"
                        >randomly assigned wrong labels</strong
                    >, the AI still produces mostly correct answers. The AI
                    cares more about <em>seeing the structure</em> (input ‚Üí output)
                    than whether your example answers are right.
                </p>
                <div class="f-takeaway">
                    ‚Üí This means: the format of your examples is doing most of
                    the heavy lifting, not the content accuracy.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="finding">
            <div class="f-icon">üìê</div>
            <div class="f-body">
                <h4>Finding 2: Even random labels beat no labels</h4>
                <p>
                    Providing examples with random labels still outperforms
                    zero-shot (no examples). So even imperfect examples add
                    value ‚Äî they establish the task structure and expected
                    output shape in the AI's context window.
                </p>
                <div class="f-takeaway">
                    ‚Üí This means: don't stress about getting perfect examples.
                    Good format + wrong labels &gt; no examples at all.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="finding">
            <div class="f-icon">üé≤</div>
            <div class="f-body">
                <h4>
                    Finding 3: Label distribution matters more than label
                    accuracy
                </h4>
                <p>
                    Selecting labels from a <strong style="color:#fff;"
                        >realistic distribution</strong
                    > (e.g., 60% negative, 40% positive ‚Äî matching real-world ratios)
                    helps more than using perfectly balanced or uniform labels. The
                    AI learns real-world frequencies from your examples.
                </p>
                <div class="f-takeaway">
                    ‚Üí This means: reflect real-world proportions in your
                    examples, not just balanced textbook cases.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- The random label experiment ‚Äî interactive -->
        <div class="section-title">
            üß™ The Random Label Experiment ‚Äî See It Live
        </div>
        <div class="experiment">
            <h4>ü§Ø Even wrong labels produce the right answer</h4>
            <div class="exp-desc">
                The page shows 3 versions of the same classification task. Click
                each to see what the AI does with correct labels, wrong labels,
                and inconsistent format:
            </div>
            <div class="exp-tabs">
                <div class="exp-tab active" onclick="showExp('correct', this)">
                    ‚úÖ Correct Labels
                </div>
                <div class="exp-tab" onclick="showExp('random', this)">
                    üé≤ Random (Wrong) Labels
                </div>
                <div class="exp-tab" onclick="showExp('messy', this)">
                    üå™Ô∏è Messy Format
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="exp-content active" id="exp-correct">
                <div class="prompt-wrap">
                    <div class="lbl">PROMPT</div>
                    <pre>This is awesome! // <span class="hl-label">Positive</span>
This is bad! // <span class="hl-label">Negative</span>
Wow that movie was rad! // <span class="hl-label">Positive</span>
What a horrible show! //</pre>
                </div>
                <div class="output-wrap">
                    <div class="lbl">OUTPUT</div><pre>Negative</pre>
                </div>
                <div class="exp-verdict pass">
                    ‚úÖ Correct answer. Labels are right, format is consistent.
                    Expected.
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="exp-content" id="exp-random">
                <div class="prompt-wrap">
                    <div class="lbl">
                        PROMPT ‚Äî labels are intentionally WRONG
                    </div>
                    <pre>This is awesome! // <span class="hl-label">Negative</span>  ‚Üê wrong!
This is bad! // <span class="hl-label">Positive</span>  ‚Üê wrong!
Wow that movie was rad! // <span class="hl-label">Positive</span>  ‚Üê wrong!
What a horrible show! //</pre>
                </div>
                <div class="output-wrap">
                    <div class="lbl">OUTPUT</div><pre>Negative</pre>
                </div>
                <div class="exp-verdict warn">
                    ü§Ø Still correct! AI ignored the wrong labels and understood
                    the task from the FORMAT and INPUT structure alone. The
                    labels were wrong but the AI got the right answer anyway.
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="exp-content" id="exp-messy">
                <div class="prompt-wrap">
                    <div class="lbl">PROMPT ‚Äî inconsistent format</div>
                    <pre>Positive This is awesome!
This is bad! Negative
Wow that movie was rad!
Positive
What a horrible show! --</pre>
                </div>
                <div class="output-wrap">
                    <div class="lbl">OUTPUT</div><pre>Negative</pre>
                </div>
                <div class="exp-verdict warn">
                    ü§Ø Still correct! Even with no consistent separator, no
                    consistent label placement ‚Äî the AI still figured out the
                    task. Modern models are surprisingly robust to format noise.
                    (But don't rely on this ‚Äî clean format is still best
                    practice.)
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- The Hard Limit: Reasoning -->
        <div class="section-title">
            üöß The Big Limitation ‚Äî Where Few-Shot Breaks Down
        </div>
        <div class="limit-box">
            <h4>
                ‚ùå Few-Shot Fails on Complex Reasoning ‚Äî Even with 5 Examples
            </h4>
            <p>
                The page proves this with the odd-numbers math task. Even with 4
                worked examples showing the correct answers, the AI gets the 5th
                one wrong. Why? Because the AI is learning to <em
                    >copy the output format</em
                > from examples ‚Äî but it's not being shown <em
                    >how to reason through the problem step by step</em
                >. The examples show "what" but not "how".
            </p>
            <div class="solution">
                ‚úÖ The fix: Chain-of-Thought (CoT) prompting ‚Äî the next
                technique. Instead of showing input‚Üíoutput examples, you show
                input‚Üístep1‚Üístep2‚Üíoutput. Teaching the reasoning path, not just
                the answer.
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="prompt-wrap">
            <div class="lbl">
                FEW-SHOT WITH 4 EXAMPLES ‚Äî still fails on reasoning
            </div>
            <pre>The odd numbers in this group add up to an even number: 4, 8, 9, 15, 12, 2, 1.
A: The answer is False.

The odd numbers in this group add up to an even number: 17, 10, 19, 4, 8, 12, 24.
A: The answer is True.

The odd numbers in this group add up to an even number: 16, 11, 14, 4, 8, 13, 24.
A: The answer is True.

The odd numbers in this group add up to an even number: 17, 9, 10, 12, 13, 4, 2.
A: The answer is False.

The odd numbers in this group add up to an even number: 15, 32, 5, 13, 82, 7, 1.
A:</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="output-wrap wrong">
            <div class="lbl">OUTPUT ‚Äî WRONG even with 4 examples!</div>
            <pre>The answer is True.  ‚Üê Incorrect. The correct answer is False (15+5+13+7+1 = 41, which is odd)</pre>
        </div>
        <p
            style="font-size:0.82rem;color:#94a3b8;margin-top:0.5rem;line-height:1.6;"
        >
            The AI memorized the output <em>pattern</em> ("The answer is True/False")
            but never actually did the math. It's pattern-matching, not reasoning.
            This is the ceiling of few-shot.
        </p>

        <!-- The escalation ladder -->
        <div class="section-title">
            üì∂ The Escalation Ladder ‚Äî When to Move Up
        </div>
        <div class="ladder">
            <div class="rung r1">
                <div class="r-num">1</div>
                <div class="r-text">
                    <h5>‚ö° Zero-Shot ‚Äî Always try first</h5>
                    <p>
                        Simple instruction, no examples. Fast, free, no setup.
                        Works for common tasks.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="rung-arrow">
                ‚Üì If output format is wrong or quality is poor
            </div>
            <div class="rung r2">
                <div class="r-num">2</div>
                <div class="r-text">
                    <h5>üìé Few-Shot ‚Äî Add 1‚Äì3 examples</h5>
                    <p>
                        Show the AI what you want. Fixes format issues and
                        improves consistency. Sweet spot for most tasks.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="rung-arrow">
                ‚Üì If task involves reasoning, math, or multi-step logic
            </div>
            <div class="rung r3">
                <div class="r-num">3</div>
                <div class="r-text">
                    <h5>üß† Chain-of-Thought ‚Äî Show the reasoning steps</h5>
                    <p>
                        Add step-by-step reasoning to your examples. Forces the
                        AI to think, not just pattern-match. Next page!
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="rung-arrow">
                ‚Üì If still failing on very domain-specific tasks
            </div>
            <div class="rung r4">
                <div class="r-num">4</div>
                <div class="r-text">
                    <h5>üîß Fine-Tuning ‚Äî Retrain the model on your data</h5>
                    <p>
                        Last resort. Expensive. But gives you a model that's
                        genuinely specialized for your use case.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tip-banner">
            <span style="font-size:1.4rem;flex-shrink:0;">üí°</span>
            <p>
                <strong>Key Takeaways:</strong>
                (1) Few-shot = show examples, not just instructions. Format matters
                more than label accuracy. (2) 1‚Äì3 examples is usually enough. More
                isn't always better ‚Äî it costs tokens. (3) Even wrong labels help,
                because the AI learns task structure from the format. (4) Few-shot
                hits a hard ceiling on reasoning tasks ‚Äî that's what Chain-of-Thought
                is for, which is next.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</Layout>

